Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro area countries, inflation was higher than expected in November, with an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent recorded after 2.6 per cent in October, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rates, which it believes will encourage a spiral of inflation as commodity prices rise and unemployment falls slightly.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is at a crossroads: It must "de-inflate" inflation to avoid the need for action later.
In November, the inflation rate in Germany reached a 12-year high of 3.3 percent; in Spain, it climbed from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The rise in food and energy prices is responsible for the rise in inflation in the euro area.
MATIF wheat prices rose 88 percent and soybean prices also reached a record high since 1973.
The price of cooking oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil has risen 52 percent this year - last month the price of a barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9% in 2009.
For the next three to four months, analysts expect inflation to be 3 percent, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
