Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco is up almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budauer trade area have again maintained their average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Articles from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörs shopping triangle, the price of the usual "Napi" Christmas basket has risen by 16 percent this year, but all hypermarkets have recorded price increases of over HUF 1,000.
After the food market price surge last December, the percentage of inflation has not been drastic compared with the already high initial level.
However, it is certainly a deterrent for consumers that what they paid well under HUF 9,000 for last year is not available for even HUF 10,000 this year.
The price of the 'Napi' basket exceeded the magic limit of HUF 10,000 by at least HUF 91 in the markets examined.
The highest price was HUF 10,573.
(In 6800 the price was HUF 6,800.)
Prices for unicorn and live fish remained almost at the same level as last year, while prices for turkey breast fillets, nut and poppy rose sharply.
The prices for flour and bread were in line with the data of the Hungarian Central Statistical Office, but Auchan had 1 kg of breadsticks for 139 forints.
There was no competitive price drop to below 200 forints for the product.
Also surprising here was the price of a two-liter Coca-Cola deposit bottle of under 200 forints, so the drink, including the deposit, cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, this year's "Napi" shopping cart comparison showed Auchan as the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
Our calculations show that Cora's price in the Napi shopping cart has increased by 15 percent over last year's Christmas prices, while Tesco and Auchan have increased by 18 percent each.
The difference between the cheapest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year was 12%, while the increase between the cheapest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1,480.00.
The average price increase was still 1.206.00 forints last year, but the VAT increase was noticeable in the prices last Christmas.
This was precisely the process which hit trade hard: it seemed that the department stores could not decide properly which price range to apply to each item, since the effect of the price increase on consumer behaviour was unpredictable.
(If the trader does not plan the speed of a product, he may lose substantial profits in the price range which depends on traffic intensity.)
The price of the "Napi" basket was so drastically increased last year due to VAT that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forints, while the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
This year, such extremes were not observed, since the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even the cheapest one had a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
Compared to the last two Christmas seasons, the price of everyday consumer goods in hypermarkets has risen by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily confirm the data of the Hungarian Central Statistical Office: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Office recorded an increase in price of more than 30% over a period of 12 months.
This is the case with eggs, as well as flour.)
However, if one looks at the "Napi" cart, this seems almost impossible in the latter case, since the price level of the already expensive product has risen by barely more than 10 percent even in the worst case.
Clearly, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than the oil suppliers - after all, they were able to pass on the drastic price increase to the multinationals.
In the golden trade triangle, hypermarkets do not complain; good years are being reported all the time.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at prices at all.
Large quantities of everything are bought, durable food is on pallets and on the stores.
On Wednesday morning, there were endless lines at the cash registers in all three department stores when the number of customers suddenly exploded.
However, the country is reporting a lower customer base, so many multinationals complain to pollsters that they cannot even achieve their planned turnover, not only in food but also in sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are being saved
This year, more than a thousand infections were recorded in hospitals as a result of improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding, overwork of staff - all factors that are not conducive to controlling infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, the cost of disinfectants is also reduced.
The trauma unit at János Hospital recently diagnosed an MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
There was a similar infection earlier this year.
The man who was injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but soon afterward the man had to return with an MRSA infection.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System from hospitals, according to Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
So, this is the number of infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens that have been reported in hospitals, but the dark number is probably higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria are carried in the nose by about one third of people without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as strep throat, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if the drugs are given at too high a dose or used improperly, the well-responsive bacteria will become antibiotic-resistant and spread rapidly in hospitals under the right conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently malfunctioning immune systems, but also in the elderly or in patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA is not a special infection, such incidents are part of the daily routine of the hospital.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA is not found only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wears rubber gloves and masks when they are treated, and we have the antibiotics needed for treatment", says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are screened for MRSA when they are admitted to hospital, infection cannot always be prevented.
Sampling too infrequent
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals are preventable, but current conditions and circumstances are not conducive to curbing the emergence or spread of the MDR-CoV, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is mainly found in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen patients admitted and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not as common in Hungarian hospitals.
The reason for this is that the state health insurance system does not provide any funding for this study.
Most cases are not discovered until the patient has a noticeable MRSA infection, says the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies are intended to be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always followed by hospitals.
Among outpatients or those in primary care, microbiological sampling is even less common, says Karolina Böröcz.
The savings are in the disinfectant
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks, is so important, but there are also serious shortcomings in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but local hospitals may not always be able to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often crowded, with beds close together, although epidemiologically speaking, they should be separated by at least five feet.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröcz notes, even in hospitals with less financial resources, there are savings on disinfectants, fewer nurses, many patients - all factors that contribute to the development of infections.
Such infections have been shown to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped if these protective measures are followed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infections are a huge expense to health insurance companies, so they're being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention or control of MRSA was included in the government programme.
Initial evidence shows that the programme is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made the prevention of the emergence of multi-drug resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
The death squad chief wasn't drunk.
The official report on the fatal car accident caused by the police chief of the 22nd district is now available.
The now-resigned police chief of the 22nd district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither drunk nor under the influence of drugs, Attila Morvai, the spokesman for the Budapest prosecutor's office, said on Friday after the official report on the case was submitted.
The report confirmed the results of the initial investigation, which showed that the police chief had not consumed alcohol before taking the wheel.
The former police chief drove his own car into Kossuth Lajos Road in the 22nd district and hit a 55-year-old man who crossed the road at an unmarked spot.
(However, according to StVO, this is not a mitigating factor - the driver has priority, even if pedestrians do not cross the road on the zebra strip.)
The pedestrian succumbed to his injuries after being admitted to the hospital.
Police reports say the driver suffered a shock, then resigned and requested retirement.
The Budapest prosecutor's office has opened an investigation into the incident.
In addition, Attila Morvai mentioned that the former police chief had been cooperating with the investigators from the beginning.
