Bulgaria, the EU's real estate paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all Europe is watching the Balkan country, which was rarely mentioned before.
What, where and who is buying on the EU's still cheapest market, but one that is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most desirable place to buy property in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the Renner, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the country's interior will attract investors sooner or later, for example Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the particularly advantageous area of Russe will also see more buyers.
The capital, Sofia, also offers attractive offers - commercial and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of Europe's most attractive golfing paradises, attracting tourists in the summer and winter seasons as well as in the other two.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy property in Bulgaria also want to change their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested people from France, Belgium, Spain, and increasingly from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros or run-down houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication opportunities are highlighted, but proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are also crucial for buyers.
The second category is those looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations for Germans in December).
The third group is businessmen who invest with the aim of increasing their value in the medium to long term.
The cost of housing in the capital is increasing, driven by ever-increasing demand.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the EU, it has seen an annual increase of 21% over the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six Hungarian per cent
As announced by Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out measures to reduce emissions after 2012, the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
The Commission is also proposing a new programme for the development of the European Union.
The US has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but that it would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question at the conference is whether the industrialized countries are prepared to help the developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on assistance to developing countries.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, which is expected to be part of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in the 'Piac et Profit' report.
Hungary six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leadership in global climate action and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (from 1990 levels) whether or not the 'post-2012 agreement' is achieved, and that the Union would be ready to commit to a 30% reduction if other major industrial countries and developing countries were also willing to meet their obligations responsibly and to the best of their ability.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the goal of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU, with its then 15 Member States, had already committed to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared with 1985-87 - a target which the country will certainly meet, as the press release from the Ministry of the Environment states.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012, in which case the Kyoto Protocol's reduction agenda would not be followed by a new international emissions reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific committee on climate change of the UN, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize, in its recent report.
This would delay emissions reduction and would inevitably cause the earth's average temperature to rise by more than 2°C, with the consequences, scientists say, to be extremely serious and irreparable.
British Army is advertising on YouTube
British Army units have posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube: Special Forces in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The footage, taken with miniature cameras attached to helmets, is monitored at Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where it is posted online.
The political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have contributed 139 such recordings, and their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The UK Ministry of Defence was registered under defence headquarters in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Keeping Force (IPTF) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the goal of recruiting soldiers, and the Defense Department says the posts also serve the purpose of informing the public about the true goals of foreign missions.
This kind of propaganda is almost free compared to traditional television ads, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but the videos always carry a degree of political message, as they in their own way justify the existence of government-mandated military action.
Americans advertise with games
The army also has to fight against amateur film that, along with the carefully edited, censored footage, also gets on the net - such as those showing the deaths of soldiers: The somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films only talk about the losses, but do not show the bloody sides of the war.
The video-sharing platform has already uploaded numerous videos of the war in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre".
The Americans, however, are advertising in a slightly different way, with the free-to-download shooter game "America's Army", in which the player can step into the soldier's skin in a more or less lifelike simulation.
