More and more forces are mobilized for a giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions will form their coordination committee for the indefinite strike on Friday.
On Saturday, a protest rally will be held, and on Monday, the day of the referendum on the health insurance law, the work stoppage will begin.
The strike is expected to cause significant disruption to traffic as railway services are almost completely suspended and Budapest's public transport operators (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of Monday's strike will be announced jointly by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA-MOSZ strike committee is also set up to coordinate Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a protest rally will be held, and from Monday all organizations that have joined the strike will cease work indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law, was not defined.
If the National Council does not approve the Health Insurance Act, the unions will withdraw the call for strike immediately.
If the law is passed, however, the strike committees meet to discuss the next steps.
The National Council's agenda for Monday means that it is even possible that the vote on the health insurance law will not take place until late in the evening or even before midnight.
The strikes, which will begin on Monday, will cause considerable disruption to traffic: railways will stop working indefinitely, most public transport will be stopped in the morning and more than half of Volán's communities will be closed.
At the same time, there will be one-way traffic jams in many places.
The call for the strike was followed by numerous trade unions and civil society organizations - the list of participants is updated on the League website.
Some organisations announced indefinite strikes, others planned temporary work stoppages.
As of Thursday afternoon, no agreement had yet been reached on sufficient services between the Hungarian Railway MÁV and the VDSZSZ, the Free Trade Union of Railways, despite the fact that more people are travelling by train, especially around the Christmas holidays.
According to reports so far, the BKVs are on strike from the start of operation until 1 p.m., the Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m., the LIGA electricity and heat unions are suspending work for four hours, and the teachers' union, e.g. the Democratic Teachers' Union, have called for two and two- and eight-hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association is striking nationwide at different times, alternating between them, and the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Trade Union Cooperation Forum, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and present a new approach to social discourse.
The second demand concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, due to be introduced next year.
The third requirement is that eligible occupations should be given access to the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which is part of the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer made by the Ministry of Transport for the secondary lines and is now calling for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was established in August with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, inter alia: "In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
This is reportedly seen as a failure on the part of the political authorities: "Public figures have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now based their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict".
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremism and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least because of the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, "have seriously damaged Hungary's image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We recall that since autumn 2006 the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several organizations calling themselves "National Self-Defense Association" have been founded.
"What these groups have in common is that they each define themselves as a civilian organization while openly boasting of preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defense tasks (disaster response, national defense, law enforcement), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself", it said.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to the Council and the Council, and I am sure that the Council will be able to do so.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of association is therefore not only intended to avoid legal obstacles that may arise in the course of registration before the courts - it is also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard also represent a risk factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, so some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as a confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policies.
All this has implications for the political stability of the region", it said.
The research institute considers that the creation of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, and that the political risk for the entire region has therefore increased.
The Hungarian Guard's activities are reportedly similar to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The Bulgarian Guard was formed in response to the mass massacres of Roma in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU immediately used the events as a reason to create the National Guard, arguing that the organization's goal was "national protection".
In their view, a real "gypsy terror" has been felt in Bulgaria over the past 17 years, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent.
The initiative would have sparked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As mentioned, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is also evidenced by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organisations have announced the creation of their own guards for resistance purposes.
As the activities of the Hungarian Guard have so far shown many similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that Hungarian Roma will also respond to the threats by organising their own protection, says the risk warning report by Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, research director at Political Capital, said at the news agency's request: "Risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
Risk analysis reports would be published annually and if changes in risk are apparent, public opinion would be informed, as in the case of the risk warning report.
Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of rearranging working days around holidays has now become established, but we will have fewer such days next year.
In the EU and America, too, "holiday" has a different meaning.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and days off from work.
The majority of days off are church holidays or related to important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year's Day: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are days off - the latter just so that the New Year's celebrants can rest.
We have a total of fourteen public holidays throughout the year.
The national holidays are 15 March, which commemorates the 1848 revolution, and 23 October, the anniversary of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20th, we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1st, we celebrate labor, on November 1st and 2nd, we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two public holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our national, state or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shifting" has proved successful in cases where we would work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, however, is that we have to work or go to school on the Saturdays before.
The date on which this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finally worked has been fixed for many years by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public servants and civil servants.
The only exceptions are firms and establishments where the work continues without interruption, including on public holidays.
The only thing that is causing a bit of confusion this year is the end-of-year holidays: from 24 December onwards, life in this country is virtually at a standstill, as most people take time off or a special holiday between Christmas and New Year's Eve.
Next year, more holidays will fall in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
The calendar is first "put on its head" around the working day so that people can stay home for four days in a row.
Saturday, April 26th, will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd, can be a day of rest.
The second change is linked to the holiday of 23 October: on Saturday 18 October, you will have to work in advance on Friday 24 October.
The end of the year will be marked by holidays, however, as everything will be in place from 24 December onwards, even if New Year falls on a Wednesday.
Six little things to scare off your coworkers
Emails we forget to send, voice messages we never get -- harmless lies we don't even notice anymore: they bring color into our everyday workplace.
The question is whether you get used to these little inconveniences, or whether you better face the challenge and try to deliberately avoid these misunderstandings for other annoying situations.
I'll give you a tip.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called", says a colleague.
That it's gonna make you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it, perhaps by calling the marketing department and saying that you regret forgetting to direct the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, an apology is the way to go.
Before getting involved in embarrassing excuses, you should think about what you can do to make your colleagues feel really uncomfortable and try to deliberately avoid these situations.
Borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's hardly anything more annoying than reaching for a document, office supplies, or phone, but it's not there.
Yesterday the notebook was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the pen, thought lost, discovered on a colleague's desk?
Without asking, you should not borrow from your colleagues, for they are rightly upset when they realize that something has been missing.
So don't put envelopes or post-it notes in your pocket from the office, because it could hit you: no more if you need them badly.
You're talking about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what to who?
Where and why?
If possible, information (or assumptions) about the private lives of colleagues should not be handed to everyone!
And when someone does open up and tell us his innermost secret, we should not abuse that trust!
It is better to be silent than to speak to those who are not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
You called in sick for no reason?
If you call the office to report sick because you are feeling unwell or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: Your work, unfinished business, projects with deadlines, now have to be done by your colleagues instead of you.
So don't play badly with your colleagues.
If you know the day before that you will not be able to make it to the office the next day, or that something might happen that will make you stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither your colleagues nor your boss are unexpectedly faced with the absence.
♪ Humming, peeping, making a phone call ♪
You're busy at work, but suddenly you're interrupted by the loud giggles of your colleagues?
Unintentionally overhearing a phone call you shouldn't have?
Do not annoy your colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (that are carried over their heads), trampling, constant scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very disturbing, even if they are not really into a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the other guy's fault?
If a project is not completed on time, if you have forgotten to send an important letter or important message, you should not blame others for your own forgetfulness!
If possible, avoid the office chaos or the loudness of your colleagues.
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others have been affected by them!
The question of how to make up for the mistake or make up for what has been missed is all too appropriate!
The office - a homey experience?
Pants and slacks, comfortable at home, but not lost in the office!
Even if the workplace allowed it, you should not dress so lightly!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself enough to dress appropriately in the office - if desired, even pretty and elegant!
