After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents in the archive, which cover a total of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, have so far been accessible only for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and by name, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his family.
The 11 countries responsible for its administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to make it available to researchers and historians.
Following the completion of the ratification process of this Decision, the opening is valid since yesterday.
The Commission has
The historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research, "especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health of the forced labourers", explains Reto Meistern, head of the archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents publicly available, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The lists of concentration camp inmates or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their arrest, thus paving the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal requests.
Nevertheless, a part of the scientific community shows only limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
You can't expect anything fundamentally new from these documents, said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
