The Congress approves the MIFID directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel with the parliamentary drafting, which ended today with the congressional resolution in the Senate on the amendments to the bill, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law, with the intention of allowing both regulations to enter into force by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the members of the Congress and the Senate, who in their negotiations and votes had sought to establish the best possible system to guarantee the security of investors and to regulate the activities of individual entrepreneurs, thus guaranteeing an overall efficient market.
The MIFID, which redefines the securities regulation, aims, in addition to modernising financial markets, to improve investor protection, increase the scrutiny of the Spanish Securities and Markets Authority (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive will make it possible to provide financial advice to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and will also contribute to the creation of new financial services companies (ESIs), the advisory firms that join forces with investment firms and securities firms.
It also expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, so that the regulated markets will be supplemented by multilateral securities trading systems and international trading systems, which would eventually compete with the existing economic operators.
The law obliges investment firms to disclose the main features of their business profile, the way in which they are confronted and the ways in which they deal with risks on the market and to register all the operations carried out, in order to facilitate the CNMV's control tasks.
The Economic Commission for the United States of America (ECOSOC) subsequently made further changes, with the US mortgage and banking crisis confirming the decision that the secured debt must now be considered a "complex" financial instrument because of its high risk to the investor.
The Commission has also taken advantage of the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of the fields of activity of qualified economists, 30 years after the 1977 Regulation which restricted the fields of activity reserved for economists was adopted.
The Senate, for its part, defined new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the commercial intermediary, who works for a third party, does not require authorisation from the CNMV and can offer his services to commercialise products and to attract clients simultaneously to several investment firms.
