What kind of insurance is best for me?
Motor insurance covering a possible accident caused by the driver involves a high cost, the amount of which depends on various factors, including age, gender, date of issue of the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured and its use, etc.
Owning a car is just the beginning.
Because it is even harder to find the right car insurance than the right model.
First of all, one must be clear about what we are dealing with here.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and an insured person.
This agreement shall be recorded in writing by means of an insurance contract, which stipulates that the company shall receive the agreed insurance premium and shall in return be obliged to provide the corresponding amount of compensation in the event of a loss.
The insurance premium is the price of insurance, which is composed of several factors, including age, gender, date of issue of the driving licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or its use.
Insurance companies set their prices according to statistics, so that higher accident risk also results in higher premiums.
This is why both over-25s and women have to pay less, as statistics show that these groups have a lower accident rate because of their caution.
The same applies to married people, since according to statistics and therefore according to the beliefs of companies, they are less likely to have accidents than single people.
The benefits attributed to the vehicle affect the frequency of driving and therefore the likelihood of an accident.
The more frequent the use, the more likely the damage.
The insurance companies must take into account a number of factors when setting the premium.
For this reason, the driver must also study the situation carefully to select the car insurance that best meets his personal needs.
We now list the most important points to consider when choosing insurance in order to make a choice that is not only performance-oriented but also price-oriented.
The younger generation faces many obstacles when choosing a cheap insurance policy, such as low driving experience and a "young" driving licence.
Even if a full-duty policy is the ideal insurance coverage, there are still cheaper alternatives.
The prudent driver can choose a full-helmet with deductible, so that the benefits of a full-helmet insurance are covered but at a low price.
This type of contract involves the customer paying part of the amount of the damage.
"The amount is determined before the contract is concluded and based on the amount of the insurance premium, which is higher the lower the amount to be paid", explains Luis Noguera, the main representative for Spain at First Europa, an online insurance brokerage.
Another option is extended insurance, which insures customers against external damage but not against damage to their own car.
In addition, this type of insurance would cover theft, fire and vehicle loss.
Here's a little advice.
If you are under 25, you can reduce your insurance costs and increase your credit by trying to drive safely and avoid accidents.
A credit is a reduction in the basic rate of the relevant insurance company.
On the contrary, a penalty payment involves an increase in the tariffs.
The amount of credits and penalties depends on the company and its income.
If the company has had a successful year, it can afford to increase the bonus payments", explains Noguera.
Once the 25-year mark is passed, it is easier for drivers to sign a contract, because the accident rate decreases with increasing driving experience.
The most sensible course is therefore to opt for a comprehensive insurance policy with own contribution.
 "Young people usually cannot benefit from their previous experience, both in the event of an accident and at the time of driving", explains the Spanish head of the European company, adding that the majority of accidents occur in the second year of practice after the 'fear of the novice' has been overcome.
However, for a married customer without children, it is more advisable to take out a comprehensive policy, of course only if the financial situation of the person concerned allows it.
The insurance companies consider married couples with children to be the customers with the lowest accident rate and their contributions are therefore low.
In this case, a full insurance policy with own contribution (about 300 euros) would be the best option.
They drive more relaxed overall and have a greater purchasing power, which allows them to start paying a higher contribution", notes Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, it is advisable to take out a full-contribution insurance policy (about EUR 150) or an extended insurance policy, which only applies if the credit is sufficiently high.
Finally, it must be said that car insurance is very important, not only because it protects the driver from possible accidental damage, but also because it involves high costs, which require a thorough selection to suit our personal situation.
