New fears over Russia-Ukraine gas dispute
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk that Russian fuel exports to Western Europe will be affected.
The bulk of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) pass through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it must pay for natural gas, it will be charged higher transit fees by Russia.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transit countries in talks", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments about the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine".
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up sharply.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
The NHS must control foreign workers
The Scottish National Health Service needs to improve checks on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the monitoring body.
The recommendation by the Chief Financial Officer, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish Public Health Service did not have precise figures on the number of its foreign staff.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were done correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The Chief Financial Officer has investigated staff recruited from outside the European Economic Area following the attack at Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an SUV drove through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in Britain.
The National Health Service is expected to carry out pre-employment checks on foreign workers to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although Disclosure Scotland is used by health authorities to check criminal records, the Agency has no competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The Auditor-General's report now states, among other recommendations, that the Board should adopt guidelines from the Criminal Records Excerpt, which helps employers with controls in different countries.
"Although we found references to these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out", the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities were following their pre-employment screening guidelines to a high degree but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information is available on the number of foreign healthcare workers".
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment surveys of potential NHS staff would identify people who might commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that NHS Scotland's current pre-employment tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide", he said.
The Scottish Health Authority says it currently has 1,161 foreign staff, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the Financial Controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, partly because the boards of directors had problems identifying those employees who were on indefinite leave.
The investigation further found that established control procedures were largely followed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
This includes passport, work permit and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines on pre-employment checks for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: 'It was a matter of urgency for me to do this work in the wake of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport.'
She added that the Scottish Government, working with the health authorities, would take into account the report's recommendations and ensure that best practice is reflected in updated guidelines on pre-employment screening of all staff, including those from abroad, which are due to be published next month.
