The climate on Venus may reveal a glimpse into the future of the earth
Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit show that the planet is even more like an alien twin of Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the nearest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and have similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have had conditions very similar to those on Earth, and scientists now believe that it could have been habitable.
But because of the unrestrained greenhouse effect of carbon dioxide, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation, and a slower rate of rotation, Venus took a very different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is ravaged by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which studied the planets for a year, provide a sobering glimpse into how the earth might evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar".
"Our new data allow us to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment".
