For a British scandal, this one's not particularly slippery.
No titles of nobility seem to have been sold, no politician's Parisian hotel bills paid, no extramarital toes licked.
But the revelation that a wealthy businessman had hidden donations to Britain's ruling Labour Party of over £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party had failed to report this, is something the contending Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When two months ago the Prime Minister backed away from the call for an election, insulting the British intelligentsia in a foolish way by claiming that opinion polls had no bearing on that decision, there was hope that he would offer a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly astute Liberal Democrat House leader, put it, the once-feared Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a struggling bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change the tax laws have raised business associations against the government.
The loss of personal data of 25 million people by the tax authorities was an unimaginable administrative blunder.
A trio of retired generals started a rebellion in the House of Lords in protest at cuts to military spending: being a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the diverse donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's Secretary General (and its former chief executive) has already resigned.
None of this means Brown is going to resign irrevocably.
Yet governments can reach a turning point after which they feel that it is impossible to govern.
People may not trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it's clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn't even need to be around for long, that delay is over: the public service begins to leak; cabinet ministers start to chatter; the press searches for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he'd like to deny Tony Blair, he was his first lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax records, for example, are related to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misadventures - like the long "money for titles" investigation of political party funding - voters might assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks.
The offences are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died or was completely conned.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's, of course, Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The recent political donation craze is a good example.
The garboesque Abrahams, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his benevolence.
Maybe so, but he didn't have the choice.
The laws against anonymity for big political donors are clear, and they exist for one simple reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's deal but not that it was illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions, just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's chief financial officer, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He was quick to condemn his party's violation of the law, but he watered down that determination by reaching for a familiar instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to the full measure by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law was broken, it's one thing for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr Brown has to do, like find a permanent chairman for the Independent Standards Committee on Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and move forward with a major reform of political party funding.
This would require hardliners in Labour to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to give up the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can win is through unquestioned integrity and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is the credit crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's only natural that the dorsal fins will swirl excitedly.
Now that America's housing market is in trouble, the predators are targeting the nation's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded loans spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both repayment rates and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either unrecoverable or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it had withdrawn a $1.4 billion fee levy from its U.S. consumer finance, in part because of weakness among credit card borrowers.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and delays are still low.
According to Moody's, the third-quarter slump rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in US private insolvency law in 2005 led to a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would increase again whether or not the general conditions for borrowers worsen.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
And trust in credit card-based securities is pretty strong, despite the stagnation in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, expects 2007 spending to be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct channels of infection between the housing crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt now that home loans are running dry.
However, card issuers look at cash flow rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily cause a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be advantageous to the card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage installments decrease when the value of the property is less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also be much faster and more flexible than lenders in responding to more volatile conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and completely re-evaluate the loans", says Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden underfunding crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and credit cuts push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a grimmer future.
Keep an eye out for those shark fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were due to stand trial for their role in the fraudulent scheme with former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Fastow changed their pleas to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of fraud using telecommunications for allegedly conspiring with Fastow in a secret financial fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employers.
The trial was scheduled for January.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, became known in the UK during extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, her case is the loose end of an investigation that began after Enron's collapse in 2001.
The charges initially filed against her in 2002 made Fastow aware that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron downturn.
The indictment against the bankers, dubbed the "NatWest Three", alleges they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraud with Fastow and his former top adviser Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partnership controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of countless fraudulent Enron schemes that helped drive the company into bankruptcy.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated the value of its stake in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the bank's shares in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely represented to Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in fact, the 20 million dollars went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others withdrew about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy to commit wire fraud for his role in the Enron bankruptcy.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in the Louisiana State Penitentiary.
Kopper is serving a sentence of three years and one month in a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three men was released on a $1 million bond, which required them to live in the United States pending trial.
Enron, once the nation's seventh-largest company, collapsed in bankruptcy in December 2001, after years of accounting tricks could no longer mask billions in debt or make failing businesses look profitable.
The collapse destroyed thousands of jobs, over $60 billion in market value and over $2 billion in retirement plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the Enron collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died of heart disease last year.
Not down in Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough range to fly nonstop from Moscow to Los Angeles is at least $54 million.
But that's a lot of change for some of the rich Russians.
"It can seat up to 18 passengers", said Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of you are asking for so many seats because it's for a private family or a corporate president".
Firer was at the Gulfstream booth last Friday for the Millionaire's Show, a four-day orgy of displayed consumption held at a nestled exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury vendors had set up booths, hoping to interest newly minted Russians in everything from mahogany-panelled yachts to diamond-plated car grills that would be reasonable for 50 cents.
Firer carefully targeted a shiny orange Porsche at the nearest exhibition stand.
"That's a nice car, but it's small money compared to us", he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private jets".
Fueled by an oil boom, the Russian capital seems as flooded with money as Dallas was in its heyday.
"We went through the same phase in the 1890s when some Americans got gigantic wealth and went in droves to Europe, where they were considered materialistic", said Marshall Goldman, a researcher at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard University.
Like the Saudi overflyers of the 1970s and the Japanese in the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the most visible and generous money issuers in the world.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of the gold rush.
Elsewhere in Moscow, a luxury industry conference this week drew Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell high-priced goods in markets like Russia.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, which is owned by the New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires, who have a total of $282 billion, according to Forbes' list of the richest people.
In addition, 103,000 Russian millionaires are in the second class, worth a combined $670 billion, according to a study on the development of private wealth in the former Soviet Union written by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a group of experts here.
(The World Bank says that in 2005 15.8 percent of Russians lived below the poverty line.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow - that's why we're all here", said Nicole Marais, a sales and marketing representative for David Morris, a London jeweler.
She had attended the fair for the first time with the brand's Russian dealer, Soho Jewelry Group.
"The women are all well-groomed and the men are all worth a fortune".
As they walk through the halls on Sunday night in evening clothes, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, describe themselves and their clients as millionaires.
"I've been looking at the cars and I'm trying to decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche", said Ms. Yumatova, who delivered the designer clothes she was wearing, like a red carpet veteran with Joan Rivers.
The fair seemed primarily aimed at the new rich, the type of brand-conscious Russian shoppers who would be willing to stand for hours in traffic to visit a busy warehouse that shamelessly stocked Cadillac Escalades, platinum pocket knives, Mövenpick ice cream, bespoke pool tables, Dubai apartments and Gund teddy bears.
The public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and best", said Mr. Gijrath, who sat patriotically at a booth of the Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft in front of a wall-sized imitation of a Rembrandt painting made of hand-painted blue mosaic stones.
"Of course, Russians are more interested in clipper-clippers".
In fact, dealers here say that Russians with old money (10 to 15 years old by Russian standards) have already moved from big-line logos to the kind of sober brands with limited numbers that wouldn't be marketed at a trade show.
Nevertheless, several thousand people, whether millionaires, emissaries of millionaires, or simply tourists, thronged the halls every day.
And some of them bought.
On the first night of the show last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the general manager of King Koil Beds here, said he sold two $70,000 mattress sets made of silk, cashmere and cotton with gold thread sewn into them.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, a sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that provides high-end cars with high-end alarm systems, said his company sold the bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
By Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a company that customizes luxury cars, said he had sold three car grilles for a Rolls-Royce Phantom that resemble interlocking chain-arm tires for $55,000 each.
He showed a reporter a car tire that was designed for a Russian casino owner, with spokes that he had coated with colored Swarovski crystals so that it looked like a roulette wheel.
The cost: $22,000 for a replacement.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather bikes or a picture of his wife's face made of cubic zirconium will not necessarily ride on these bikes", Mr Karapetian said.
"He'll keep it in his 30- or 40-car garage".
Even though many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaires" would not express much exclusivity at the moment, given the rise in property prices there.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you are probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash", he said.
"There are more of them than you think".
Those who were not millionaires could at least pretend to be rich at a booth run by Alliance Continental, a Russian wealth management company.
The company had set up four red British-style phone booths crammed with mountains of fake million-dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing director, said his employees had printed 500,000 fake bills for the millionaire's fair.
Passersby stopped to toss around the piles of money, take cell phone photos while they were reclining in the middle of the surrogate wealth, get friends to snap them, or just to steal a few million.
"Look, in Moscow, anyone can feel like a millionaire", Mr. Karryev said.
Failed surgery suspected in New Jersey fatality
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Ronald Livingston looked out the big glass window of the Just a Little Healthier restaurant here and watched an ambulance pull up on the white Cape Cod two doors down on West Scott Avenue.
Soon there was a police car.
And then there was another one.
"Then I saw the medical examiner's boxcar approach", said Livingston, a restaurant supervisor, on Wednesday.
"That's when I knew someone had died".
Authorities learned that the dead woman was Olga Arroyo, 41, an assistant to the director of the Newark Police Department.
Now investigators are trying to determine if she died from a procedure performed by an unlicensed plastic surgeon, who police did not identify, who worked at the home at 212 West Scott Avenue.
Authorities have yet to determine the cause of Ms. Arroyo's death, and are hopeful that toxicology tests, the results of which may not be available for weeks, will help unravel a mysterious death that has sent shockwaves through the top brass of Newark police.
Ms. Arroyo had been an assistant to the police chief, Garry F. McCarthy, since September 2006, and her voice was familiar to many in the department.
"She was loyal, hardworking and persistent", Mr McCarthy said of Ms Arroyo in a telephone interview on Wednesday.
"She was my pit bull.
She protected me".
McCarthy said Mrs. Arroyo was the wife of Jimmy Arroyo, a former New York City police officer who works for the Alcohol Enforcement Administration, and that she leaves behind two sons, 14 and 11, and a stepdaughter.
Eileen Walsh, a spokeswoman for Union County Prosecutor Theodore J. Romankow, said investigators would try to determine if Arroyo died as a result of unauthorized surgery.
"That's one of the ways", said Mrs. Walsh.
"It's an ongoing investigation".
Authorities said they arrived at the house around 3 p.m. in November.
And they found Mrs. Arroyo on a couch.
She was pronounced dead at the scene.
More than a week has passed and authorities have said little about their investigation or the owner of the house, who is listed as Flor Margarita Castro.
Walsh wouldn't say if Ms. Castro was questioned by the authorities.
Investigators are trying to determine if part of the house was used as a medical practice.
On Wednesday, no one answered the door to Mrs. Castro's house, where a withered rose bush stands in the narrow front yard and a Dalmatian barks behind the house.
A blue barrel labeled "Ethyl Vanillin" - used as a substitute for vanilla in food and perfume - sat in the parking lot next to a door that led to the basement.
Two mountain bikes were hanging by hooks on one side.
McCarthy said that when he first arrived in Newark after spending 25 years with the New York Police Department, Mrs. Arroyo was invaluable in helping him navigate the provincial and harsh political culture of his new city.
"She said, 'You have to pay attention to this or that,'" he said.
"She was always here when I came here and she was always here when I left.
It was embarrassing".
Hopes that the central bank will cut interest rates will lead to a rise in world stock markets
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after market hopes that the central bank will try to calm credit markets by further interest rate cuts were bolstered by soothing comments from the vice chairman of the US central bank.
Stock markets rose in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kahn, the number two to Ben Bernanke, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that policy must respond "flexibly and pragmatically" to the ongoing pressure on financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm sluggish markets, in the face of signs of emerging credit tensions, Kohn said the recent turbulence had "partially reversed some of the improvements in market functioning from the late part of September and October".
If the increased turbulence persists, it would increase the possibility of further tightening financial conditions for consumers and businesses, he said.
The comments were seen by investors as a signal that the central bank is ready to step in and stabilise credit conditions with new capital injections into US markets and possible further interest rate cuts.
The comments also helped to calm Wall Street, amid further bad news from the US economy, now that US property sales hit a new record low in October.
The impact of the financial turmoil was underscored by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would cut 650 jobs, or 4 percent of its global workforce, in a cost-cutting move to offset heavy losses from its losing bets in the U.S. mortgage sector.
Only 20 of these jobs are expected to disappear in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S&P 500 Index rose 2.65 percent.
In London, the FTSE 100 Index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6,306.2, adding more than £39 billion to the value of British stocks.
Germany's Dax index rose by 2.6 percent and France's CAC40 rose by 2.3 percent.
The re-emergence of credit pressures on the markets had previously been underlined by strong demand at an auction of three-month guarantees from the European Central Bank granted to European commercial banks, which were awarded at a remarkable 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England, the US central bank and the European Central Bank to follow suit and inject more capital into London's money markets increased as credit tensions saw three-month Libor rates on UK banks' borrowing rise by 6.59 percent to their highest since late September, after a steady rise since November 21.
England faces a decision on the statements of Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara
Here are two dilemmas, each almost as difficult as the other.
Who will be the number six for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, no less relevant in a broader context than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is important because David Graveney, the chairman of the election committee, on call at least under this special title, is here to help head coach Peter Moores and captain Michael Vaughan decide, and because the table of High Morries, the English managing director, is gradually filling up with applications for national election offices, if not even for some part-time.
Whoever doesn't get the sixth batting position will be unhappy, but life is often unfair and sports is no doubt unfair.
It is never easy to pinpoint exactly what enables one person to reach the top of his profession while another never rises above the lowest rank, sometimes due to lack of luck rather than ability.
It's not just in cricket where choices are difficult, where judgments are necessary, which are always subjective in the end.
Is this the right time for Bopara to step up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same question may be asked in another area, whether, for example, John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both intelligent young executives with good degrees who know the business well, should be promoted.
Who can tell what the right class is for a cricketer unless he is given the opportunity to swim or sink.
Of course, numbers have a big impact on decisions, but so do chances.
Within a team, a cricketer must catch the eye of the captain at the right time when he can take a wicket and a batsman must get regular chances on the order if he wants to impress as a one-day cricketer.
It's more complicated to get the voters' attention.
There were many who were better last season than, say, James Anderson, who will apparently play in the first Test even though Stephen Harmison declares himself healthy and the wind is blowing in the nets.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs apiece to earn a place in this tour.
Chris Tremlett only took 29 with the same modest average, but both had their high points and hope for more.
Whether Shah or Bopara plays at Asgiriya Stadium can only be a matter of opinion.
The election could decide both men's careers, or it might make little difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played every Test and was successful in the first, taking five wickets and 40 useful runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, then still struggling to establish himself, who made the breakthrough into a major Test cricketer and who, although he scored a double century against Australia in Australia, may still be underrated.
It is likely that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, following further discussion in today's webinar at Asgiriya Stadium, will follow their conservative instincts and gut feeling for Shah's greater experience of Bopara's youthful enthusiasm.
There are arguments for both.
Shah speaks for his sparkling and valuable 88 Test debut innings in Bombay, 43 first-class centuries and only six by Bopara, who at 22 years old is seven years younger, and an excellent record against a curveball.
But Shah scored just ten runs in his two innings in May against West Indies in the Test at Lord's, his home ground as a Middlesex player, and this, coupled with his immediate rejection by the selectors when Vaughan was healthy to reclaim his position for the next game, seems to have taken the momentum from his batting, which was still evident in Bombay.
In contrast, the Essex jack of all trades has a shovel-like zest for life.
He is unimpressed by anything on a cricket field and his attitude away from it was brought to a head when he recently ran over a four-wheel-drive vehicle at an exhibition for England's sponsor Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and probably a shock, but the first thing he did was to take out his Vodafone (which was also sponsored, of course) and call his teammate Alastair Cook, who was watching from a distance, and say with enthusiasm, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is a much better outfielder, he bowls his medium pace with some impact here on the pitch, which seems to suit him and he hits with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right man is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Maybe that's the real art of selection.
I'm inclined to give Bopara his chance now, which doesn't mean Shah might not look good if, as the Ceylon tea set suggests, he's the one playing here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and to fight al-Qaeda
The first busloads of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, with a flood of displaced people who have run out of funds or visas, and others hoping the city will return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the rebels who had driven them from their homes.
At Mansour Bus Station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was busy with refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned in private transports.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad", said Sabah Al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspaper about what happened in Baghdad and how it would be safe now".
They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people", he said, referring to the Shiite militias of militant cleric Moqtada Al-Sadr, who ordered his forces to withdraw at this time.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from the predominantly Sunni part of Amariyah, returned with his two children because he could not renew his Syrian visa and because the regime does not allow Iraqis to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him to tell him that a local US-backed militia had helped drive al-Qaeda from its stronghold in the west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan was the leader of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who had been driven from his home in Sleikh, north of Baghdad, by a hand grenade attack after calling on his fellow citizens to fight al-Qaeda.
He came back to fight.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they were starting an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my boys.
That's why I came back today", said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they were attracted by the increasing calm in the capital since the US troop surge and the growth of local "groups of concerned citizens" who are armed and working with the US military to defend their neighborhoods.
But more spoke of being forced to return home by visa problems and a lack of funds in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, expressed the general suspicion among the exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose visa restrictions on the refugees in order to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people are believed to have fled the country's sectarian death squads.
"We were doing well until al-Maliki visited Syria and the government pressed to stop issuing visas to Iraqis to force them to return to Iraq", the Sunni pensioner said.
"I can't trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house after I left".
Part of the reason for the decline in violence is that Sunnis have been driven out of Shia neighborhoods and vice versa, creating many places where tensions have eased.
There are fears that a sudden influx of refugees will reignite sectarian tensions and lead to conflict.
Small Saarland, good education
The smallest federal state is a leader in vocational training and even excels in the international orientation of its universities.
The Saarland has the same deficit in education as the rest of the country in only one area.
"I told a non-Saarlander for the 50th time yesterday that we are not French" - this slogan is self-deprecatingly posted by the smallest federal state on its 50th birthday.
France and Luxembourg play a major role in the Saarland education system, which is ranked fifth in the Education Monitor of the Institute of German Economics in Cologne (IW).
The universities have traditionally cooperated closely with neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded in 1948 by the French.
To this day, students here can complete their studies with a double or even triple diploma.
The proportion of foreign students is therefore high, at 15.6 per cent.
But the Saarland also attracts higher-educated rural children - many of them without a high school diploma.
"In the Saarland, the vocational education system is used", says Axel Plünnecke, an education expert at the IW.
More than one in five young people acquire their right to study at a vocational school, which is more than seven percentage points above the federal average.
The possibilities for combining vocational and academic training are also relatively extensive.
The second best in Germany is the number of people who have dual education.
However, despite practical training and growing demand, the number of graduates in engineering has fallen by a third in recent years.
The Saarland Ministry of Education has therefore now committed the universities to a marketing campaign for engineering subjects.
"We have started a number of reforms in the general education sector after the first Pisa study", says a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
The government introduced nationwide comparative tests.
To help children start learning earlier, the last year of kindergarten is free of charge - a model that other states are now copying.
Whether the students' performance improves in the long term will be shown only by future comparative studies.
In Pisa 2003, the proportion of at-risk students fell from 29 to 20 percent.
Overall, however, the Saarland did not grow as much as other Länder.
The Bavarians are better.
And to the chagrin of the Saarlanders, foreign language skills are not measured at Pisa - otherwise you could score in this area.
Because the language of the neighbors is compulsory in high schools - even if the Saarlanders are not French.
