Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its inhospitable atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European spacecraft Venus Express has detected lightning in the atmosphere and winds at the poles, as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that it's lightning on Venus.
Now the European probe Venus Express has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere, shooting lightning on Venus from cloud to cloud at a height of about 35 miles [56 km], reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the science magazine Nature.
According to the famous "soup theory", lightning caused life on earth: storms in the ocean stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
"If there was ever life on Venus, it must have been very early in history", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, the surface of Venus is likely to be almost devoid of life: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures can reach 500 degrees Fahrenheit [500°C].
"Venus may be the devil's twin of the Earth, but she is a twin", said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has taken such a completely different course is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of Venus, since no spacecraft has been on the way to explore the planet since the early 1990s.
The researchers believe that the latest research, now presented in several Nature articles, highlights more than the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that our neighbouring planet has more in common with Earth than was previously thought", the ESA reports.
The researchers found that in addition to the already known North Pole cyclone, there is a cloud vortex at the South Pole that is spinning much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-smallest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the earth and is almost the same size at 7,500 miles [12,100 km] in diameter.
Also called the Morning Star or the Evening Star, the planet orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it rotates much more slowly around itself: a day of Venus lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus' surface temperature is 460 degrees Celsius and its pressure 92 bar, it is hardly similar to Earth's, but scientists believe that both planets formed under very similar conditions.
Both of them were filled with water, which was left on Earth in oceans, but on Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is fixed in carbonate rocks, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
