These aren't Warhol's boxes.
If you think of Sweden and a wooden box, you think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
- Is that right?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden cast a dark shadow on Warhol's catalogue of works.
Most of the ninety-four Brillo boxes listed there are fake.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo boxes a few months ago, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now lead to a sobering conclusion: The six Brillo boxes bequeathed to Moderna Museet in 1995 by former museum director Pontus Hultén are copies - and probably most of the other around a hundred Brillo boxes of the "Stockholm type" in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is intertwined, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 featured - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes: these did not come from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were supplied directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but models of them, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol apparently granted permission in 1968 to have a few wooden Brillo boxes produced in Sweden, which were not, however, exhibited at Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes that have rightly entered the history of art and auctions as authorized original Andy Warhol brillo boxes with the designation "type Stockholm".
Some of them have sold for over $100,000 at auction.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968 and that Warhol then left them to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at Moderna Museet, examined the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, as well as three from private Swedish ownership, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968.
The structure of the 1990 copies, however, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press sheet with a paint roll without grounding - and it is not oil, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes", says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet. "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York reaches a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material".
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious allegations" made about the boxes of soap.
But since then, they have been in relentless silence.
